children.text: There have not been flashings installed inside the cavity between the brick veneer and the internal timber stud wall, which will allow water and moisture to continue down the cavity and into the ceiling or drain through into the ceiling/roof space down onto the plaster ceiling.
It is a requirement of Australian Standard AS 4773.2 Masonry in Small Buildings – Construction clause 9.6.2.4 Flashing at Roof Abutment that

‘Where a roof abuts a masonry wall, a through-flashing shall be installed above the roof to prevent water penetration to lower wall areas. Where the wall/roof junction is inclined or sloped, a stepped cavity ‘cascade’ flashing shall be provided’ .

It is extremely important that these flashing are properly installed in accordance with these requirements of the Australian Standards so that this home complies with the NCC’s Building Code of Australia (BCA), and also to prevent the plaster and framework from rotting out due to the ingress of water and moisture from within the brick cavity.
